the transport vesicles that move material between different compartments of the cell. For both viruses and vesicles, we aim to understand how the building blocks come together to form the virus/vesicle, how they change structure and arrangement during the lifetime of the virus/vesicle, how they obtain their lipid membranes, and how they enter or fuse with a new cell or cellular compartment.

To do this, we need to get detailed 3D images of viruses and vesicles under conditions that are very close to ?real-life?. This is technically challenging, so we are also working on developing new methods in electron microscopy and in computational image analysis.

In the longer term we want to obtain a level of knowledge about these systems that can be envisaged as a 3D movie of the assembly of the virus/vesicle, with molecular resolution. We would like to use this information to find out how small molecules or antibodies can interfere with influenza virus or HIV-1 particles as they assemble, become infectious and enter a new cell.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>The goal of this research programme is to develop and apply electron microscopy and tomography techniques to study the assembly and fusion mechanisms of enveloped viruses, as well as of coated trafficking vesicles.

Enveloped viruses and coated trafficking vesicles are extraordinary self-assembling machines. The protein building blocks must interact with one another to collect all relevant components and/or cargo together at the assembly site, they must reshape a lipid bilayer to form the bounding membrane of the virus/vesicle, and they must drive a membrane scission process to release the virus/vesicle from the donor membrane. The virus/vesicle typically then undergoes a reassembly or disassembly proves to prepare for fusion with a target membrane. We aim to obtain a detailed, mechanistic understanding of these processes and of how they are regulated.

To achieve this goal we need to obtain detailed structural information at different stages during assembly under close-to-native conditions. This is a challenge for conventional structural biology tools so we are developing and applying new approaches for cryo-electron tomography, correlated fluorescence and electron microscopy, and image processing.

The main systems being studied are influenza virus, human immunodeficiency virus, clathrin-coated vesicles, and COPI-coated vesicles. For both influenza virus and human immunodeficiency virus, we will attempt to understand the mechanisms by which small molecules or antibodies can interfere with assembly, maturation or fusion.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2017-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>241316</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>1E015575-FC35-4795-90F5-F01316282E70</gtr:id><gtr:title>Immature HIV-1 lattice assembly dynamics are regulated by scaffolding from nucleic acid and the plasma membrane.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/22f9bd69def78ceff3f7bc97266f78e9"><gtr:id>22f9bd69def78ceff3f7bc97266f78e9</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Pak AJ</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2017-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0027-8424</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>5a8035a7bfefd8.73081641</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>63ABF5FB-6DB4-4719-872D-75DFDE0F921F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Structure and assembly of the Ebola virus nucleocapsid.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Nature</gtr:paren